<TITLE> Who are the Argentines? </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Oct 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Argentines voted on Sunday for a new president. Here are some facts about the people and culture of South America's second biggest country. In a land full of national passions, Argentina's beef culture stands out. Argentines consume a whopping yearly average of about 143 lbs (65 kg) of beef per person. Meat prices are kept affordable by government price controls and export limits. Buenos Aires, the capital, is enjoying a renaissance as one of Latin America's top tourist destinations. A regional trendsetter for fashion, music and restaurants, the city became the first in Latin America to approve same-sex civil unions, cultivating a lively gay tourism industry. Despite defeat by the British military in 1982, Argentina continues to lay claim to the Falkland Islands, known as the Islas Malvinas in Spanish. Diplomatic relations have been restored but tensions persist over fishing licenses and off-shore oil exploration near the South Atlantic archipelago. Argentina's diverse territory stretches from tropical zones in the north to the chilly Patagonian region. Visitors are drawn to its glaciers, whale-watching expeditions, and snow-capped mountains, as well as to Ushuaia, the world's southernmost city. Soccer is an obsession in Argentina, home of the great Diego Maradona. The country comes to a halt twice a year for matches between its two most popular clubs -- Boca Juniors and River Plate. The games between the fierce rivals are known as the "Superclasic
